NEW PROGRAMMERS BE WARNED - as an experienced programmer, I installed this app to review some quick Python basics. It was sad to see that not only are a lot of the lessons out of order, but also inaccurate. For example, the operator precedence lesson for Python indicates that all boolean operators have equal precedence, when in reality they do NOT have equal precedence (Sololearn, I challenge you to go check the Python documentation and compare it to the erroneous guide you all posted). From greatest to least greatest precedence, the boolean operators should be ordered as: Not, And, Or. Fortunately, there are public comments for every single slide, so a lot of confusion is mitigated via these, but overall I can probably point out at least 5 to 10 other spots where a beginner would get easily confused by these lessons. If you want to truly learn programming, grab yourself a real, physical book, with legit examples and thorough explanations. It really doesn't cost that much...you'll thank not just me, but yourself later. Please thumbs up this review so that others striving to learn programming make the first step in the right direction as well - a physical book with proper lessons, not these terribly ordered quick concept cards occasionally sprinkled with misleading information.
replyContent:
Thanks for your report.

The table in the lesson can indeed be confusing.
We have added a note to clarify the table.

We really appreciate your feedback and help in making SoloLearn an even better place for coders.

Sololearn is an app that is designed to help you learn various programming languages on your phone. Developed by Sololearn the app offers introduction lessons to the session that you‚Äôre working on, as well as a community forum for each problem. The learning style offers various techniques such as multiple choice and fill in the blank.   The design is very intuitive, offering the various languages, challenges and community Q&A right from the home screen. The app also offers achievement levels based on your completed challenges and activity in the forums. In addition to the navigation on the homescreen there is also a search function that allows you to see all of the topics based on your search criteria.   This is a great tool to get kids interested in programming in school. The flexibility of the mobile application means that any device can be used to teach you the basics. Also having the community tied into the lessons means that the teacher doesn‚Äôt have to be an expert on every language to have their students learn it! Though one drawback to the style is it is easy for a student to pass the lessons without fully learning the logic behind the code that they are using.

Easy to use, concepts are explained in just enough detail, the content is very well-edited and updated according to use feedback (unlike similar apps), and the community is very active.  The only negative is that the tests are perhaps too easy. It's virtually impossible to get questions wrong as the answers required are very basic and based from the previous page that you just saw. There is also no followup or revision testing as there is in Enki (though Solo Learn is superior in every other way).  It does make sense to have progression be simple and easy (it drives engagement and ensures people stick with the app/course - Duolingo does this extensively). At the same time, it'd be useful for opt-in testing (i.e. each course could have a fluency score which fades over time unless you "train" and do tests).

Quizzes let you review past material and ensure that you retain what you learn. You can challenge other SoloLearners in 5-question programming quizzes for XP. A level system motivates you to keep learning and become the very best.  In addition to all of this, you can engage and talk directly with the community through the built-in forums! Here you can partake in coding challenges and ask programming-related questions, among other things.  If you're interested in learning how to program or want to become a better programmer, then I highly, HIGHLY recommend you download SoloLearn.

I found SoloLearn to be a good way to get a grasp of the basics of a new language. The interface is decent, the lessons are presented in small chunks, which aided the learning process, and the encouragements are helpful.  Some explanations and examples could have been more clear, but the comments and community help a lot. This is the case with many courses - you usually have to go cross-referencing with other sources of information and learn from other learners. I really like the playground area - it is a must to try coding examples as part of learning a language. To be able to do all of this from my phone is great. I took the Python course to get an overview of the language. I usually just dive into examples when I need to use an unfamiliar tool, but I wanted to get a better grounding this time, and SoloLearn worked for me. Learning Python is a step in a larger plan to learn to utilize machine learning. A machine learning course would be great, maybe even TensorFlow.  At any rate, I would recommend SoloLearn as a quick and convenient way to learn the basics of Python. It is a good launching point for a learning experience.

Often times the answers they ask you after each tutorial can be completely unrelated to the current tutorial.  All of this review is based off completion of one language (Java). I will likely edit my review once I have more time with this app. Oh and before I forget the app asking me for a review several times before I finish a tutorial is slightly annoying. This may seem like a negative review but overall I must say I am very pleased with this app. I just wanted to give some positive criticism so hopefully some of these issues can be addressed.  7/3/17 - After a few months of using this app I felt like an update to my review was appropriate. Some of my previous issues with the app still apply most don't, for example it still asks me to review the app in the middle of tutorials. But that is such a minor annoyance compared to everything this app has taught me. The courses I talked about on my previous review about unrelated tutorial questions isn't so bad now since they keep adding new things to the tutorials and adding new tutorials too! With all that being said this app deserves more than the 5 stars I can give it. Thank you Sololearn for this amazing app and keep doing what your doing!

______________Synopsis_____________ An amazing free with no adds app, which helps get you started in many programming languages in a really enjoyable manner.   _____Does It Have What I Need?_____ 1. I'm certain that later on you can use your saved codes and your profile in general in your portfolio.   2. It has a separate comment section in every lesson in each course in order to get help from other users.  3. You can also follow and invite users as well as it has its own forum section to ask and answer questions.  _______I Need MOTIVATION_______ It facilitates a system that has XP points and levels which rise with learning and challenging other users in 5 questions challenges and many more.

Love this app! Very well organized content, both in terms of how the notions are presented, and interactivity by inserting mini-tests throughout every chapter.  Important to mention here is the "try-it yourself" code module, which allows users to write their own code.  Then, the comments section, in which one can read other people opinions and write their own comments and questions. And the challenge-tests, they are both fun and instructive.  Then, I believe the "incentive" system with points, badges, etc is very well thought, to motivate the person who is learning. It is also very useful that it is one single app that integrates all the courses, instead of having separate apps for java, html, css etc. Though the level of the notions presented in these courses is far from being called advanced or comprehensive, the app does a very good job at initiating one in html, css, java, sql, etc. After one completes a course in SoloLearn, will be much easier to read and *understand* online documentation. In two words, this app makes learning fun, and keeps you motivated!

The examples on the site are often oversimplified, incomplete or just plain wrong.  It fosters a false sense of accomplishment.  The educational experience is reduced to a game in which you seek levels of experience to unlock badges.  It does not foster deep understanding of basic and vital concepts such as the importance of code hygeine for readability and maintainability.  The user-submitted challenges are often so poorly formatted or unrealistically convoluted that you run out of time trying to decipher them, but those who are rewarded care nothing about making quality code and haven't got a thorough understanding.  The examples and quizzes are far too trivial.  The comment sections are too short and with no character count to indicate when you exceeded size, so that when you submit 20 minutes worth of finger diddling your mobile device, it just drops your submission saying No Connection with no chance to go back and edit.  That said, the platform itself is designed well enough to deliver content of this nature.  But they need to develop more competent material and pedagogical technique, and cover meta-topics such as build systems, design patterns and code hygeine.  And de-emphasize or remove the game aspects.

Contains thorough tutorials for several coding languages. After you finish the tutorials, continue improving your skills by participating in user-written "challenges" against other users in order to collect badges. Tutorial lessons usually involve a short article on each structure followed by a short quiz. Experience points are earned by completing lessons and challenges and can be traded for hints and other shortcuts. There is no reference library in this app, although you can revisit tutorial material in any order after completion of that material.

Helpful but the lessons are far more complicated than the quizzes. It's like teaching someone calculus and then testing them by asking them what they "10+_ = 20". It also doesn't use best practices either. As an example, it'll often test you to call a Javascript function but when you're tested it doesn't require you to use parenthesis (nor does it include them itself) when it should. This is fine for people who know better but it's bad for someone trying to learn as it could form bad habits. It's still informative and useful but does little (important) things wrong.
